Helper functions for library importing¶

This helper function checks whether a given Python library is installed by attempting to import it. If the import fails due to a missing module (ImportError), it automatically installs the library using pip and confirms the installation.

In [3]:
import importlib
import subprocess
import sys

# Check for library and if not yet installed, install
def check_library(library):
    try:
        importlib.import_module(library)
        print(f"{library} is installed.")
    except ImportError:
        print("Not yet installed. Installing now...")
        subprocess.check_call([sys.executable, "-m", "pip", "install", library])
        print(f"{library} installed.")

Handle missing values¶

This function computes missing values for each column in a PySpark DataFrame, distinguishing between numeric (NULL or NaN) and string (NULL or empty string) values. It aggregates the missing value counts in a single operation, converts the result into a dictionary, and prints the missing values for each column while handling potential errors when collecting the results.

Check for missing values¶

In [9]:
# Initialize an empty list to store aggregation expressions
agg_exprs = []

# Iterate over all columns and their data types in the DataFrame
for column, dtype in df_posts.dtypes:
    if dtype in ['int', 'double', 'float']:
        # Count missing values (NaN or NULL) for numeric columns
        expr = sum(when(col(column).isNull() | isnan(col(column)), 1).otherwise(0)).alias(column)
    elif dtype == 'string':
        # Count missing values for string columns (NULL or empty strings "")
        expr = sum(when(col(column).isNull() | (col(column) == ""), 1).otherwise(0)).alias(column)
    else:
        # Count missing values (NULL only) for other data types
        expr = sum(when(col(column).isNull(), 1).otherwise(0)).alias(column)
    
    # Append the computed aggregation expression to the list
    agg_exprs.append(expr)

# Perform a single aggregation operation to count missing values per column
missing_counts_df = df_posts.agg(*agg_exprs)

# Safely collect the result as a single row and convert it to a dictionary
try:
    missing_counts = missing_counts_df.collect()[0].asDict()
    
    # Print missing value counts for each column
    print("Missing value counts per column:")
    for col_name, cnt in missing_counts.items():
        print(f"{col_name}: {cnt}")
except Exception as e:
    print(f"Error while retrieving missing value counts: {e}")

Tags¶

This code cleans the Tags column by removing angle brackets and filling missing values before tokenizing the tags into an array. It then computes the number of tags per post as TagsCount.

In [13]:
# Remove angle brackets < > from the Tags column and replace them with spaces to ensure clean tag separation
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn("Tags", trim(regexp_replace("Tags", "<(.*?)>", "$1 ")))

# Fill any remaining NULL values with an empty string to avoid processing errors
df_posts = df_posts.na.fill({"Tags": ""})

# Ensure there are no fully empty strings by replacing them with a placeholder (if necessary)
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn("Tags", when(col("Tags") == "", "empty_tag").otherwise(col("Tags")))

# Define a tokenizer that splits the cleaned "Tags" column into an array of individual tags
tags_tokenizer = Tokenizer(inputCol="Tags", outputCol="TagsTokens")

# Apply the tokenizer to transform the dataframe
df_posts = tags_tokenizer.transform(df_posts)

# Create a new column TagsCount that stores the number of tags assigned to each post
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn("TagsCount", size(col("TagsTokens")))

Text (Title and Body)¶

This combines the Title and Body into a single text column, tokenizes the text into words, removes common stopwords, and computes text statistics such as word count and total character length.

In [15]:
# This creates a new column Text that merges the title and body with a space separator
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn("Text", concat_ws(" ", col("Title"), col("Body")))

# Define a Tokenizer that splits the combined text into words
text_tokenizer = Tokenizer(inputCol="Text", outputCol="TextTokens")

# Apply the tokenizer to transform the dataframe
df_posts = text_tokenizer.transform(df_posts)

# Define a StopWordsRemover to filter out common stop words from the tokenized text
stopwords_remover = StopWordsRemover(inputCol="TextTokens", outputCol="FilteredTextTokens")

# Apply stop word removal to transform the dataframe
df_posts = stopwords_remover.transform(df_posts)

# Remove the original TextTokens column and rename FilteredTextTokens back to TextTokens
df_posts = df_posts.drop("TextTokens").withColumnRenamed("FilteredTextTokens", "TextTokens")

# Create a new column "TextWordCount" that stores the number of words in the tokenized text
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn("TextWordCount", size(col("TextTokens")))

# Create a new column "TextLength" that calculates the total character length of all words in the text
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn("TextLength",F.expr("aggregate(TextTokens, 0, (acc, token) -> acc + length(token))"))

CreationDate¶

This extracts temporal features from the post's creation date, including the hour, weekday, and month of posting. Additionally, it calculates the age of each post in days based on the end of the dataset creation date.

In [17]:
# Create new column HourOfDay (= time of posting)
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn("HourOfDay", hour(col("CreationDate")))

# Create new column Weekday (= day of posting)
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn("Weekday", date_format(col("CreationDate"), "EEEE"))

# Create new column Month (= month of posting)
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn("Month", date_format(col("CreationDate"), "MMM"))

# Create new column PostAge (= days since post is online) -> if CreationDate is NULL, set PostAge to 1
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn(
    "PostAge",
    when(col("CreationDate").isNotNull(), datediff(lit("2024-10-1"), col("CreationDate")))
    .otherwise(lit(1))
)

# This column indicates whether a post has been closed (1) or remains open (0)
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn("Closed", when(col("ClosedDate").isNotNull(), 1).otherwise(0))

# This column calculates the number of days between post creation and closure, but only for closed posts
df_posts = df_posts.withColumn(
    "OpenToCloseDays",
    when(col("Closed") == 1, datediff(col("ClosedDate"), col("CreationDate"))).otherwise(None)
)

These are all the variables retrieved from the dataset and the one's derived from it. In further steps created dataframe will be like a database, which the needed variables for the task are retrieved from:

Identifier¶
  1. ID: Unique identifier for each post in the dataset.
Text¶
  1. Title: The title of the post, summarizing its content.
  2. Body: The full text of the post, including the main question or discussion.
  3. Text: Combined text content of the title and body for analysis.
  4. TextTokens: Tokenized version of the text, represented as an array of words.
  5. TextLength: The total number of characters in the text.
  6. TextWordCount: The number of words in the text.
Tags¶
  1. Tags: A string representation of the tags associated with the post.
  2. TagsTokens: Tokenized version of the tags, stored as an array.
  3. TagsCount: The number of tags assigned to the post.
Date¶
  1. CreationDate: Timestamp indicating when the post was created.
  2. HourOfDay: The hour (0-23) when the post was created.
  3. Weekday: The day of the week the post was created (e.g., Monday, Tuesday).
  4. Month: The month in which the post was created.
  5. PostAge: The age of the post in days since the creation relative to 1.10.2024 (End Q3).
Closed Questions¶
  1. ClosedDate: Timestamp indicating when the post was closed, if applicable.
  2. Closed: A binary variable (1 if the post is closed, 0 if it remains open).
  3. OpenToCloseDays: The number of days between creation and closure of the post.
Score¶
  1. Score: The overall score of the post, typically based on upvotes and downvotes.
  2. ViewCount: The total number of times the post has been viewed.
  3. AnswerCount: The number of answers submitted for the post.
  4. CommentCount: The number of comments associated with the post.

Tags Wordcloud¶

This analyzes the frequency of tags in a dataset by breaking multi-tag entries into separate rows, counting occurrences, and selecting the top 200 most frequent tags. It then creates a word cloud visualization, where the size of each word represents its frequency in the dataset.

In [28]:
# Explode array of tags into multiple rows (each containing 1 tag)
df_tags_analysis_exploded = df_tags_analysis.withColumn("TagsTokensExploded", explode(col("TagsTokens")))

# Group by the exploded tags and count how many times each tag appears
df_tags_analysis_exploded = df_tags_analysis_exploded.groupBy("TagsTokensExploded") \
                                                     .agg(count("*").alias("TagsSum"))

# Order tags by frequency (descending order)
df_tags_analysis_exploded = df_tags_analysis_exploded.orderBy(desc("TagsSum"))

# Collect the top 200 most frequent tags for visualization
try:
    df_tags_rows = df_tags_analysis_exploded.limit(200).collect()
except Exception as e:
    print(f"Error while collecting top tags: {e}")
    df_tags_rows = []

# Convert collected data into a dictionary for the word cloud
df_tags_wordfreq = {row['TagsTokensExploded']: row['TagsSum'] for row in df_tags_rows}

# Generate the word cloud from tag frequencies
wordcloud_tags = WordCloud(width=1200, height=800, background_color="white").generate_from_frequencies(df_tags_wordfreq)

# Plot the word cloud
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.imshow(wordcloud_tags, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Wordcloud Tags")
plt.show()

The word cloud highlights the most commonly used tags in the dataset. Larger words, such as "python," "javascript," and "reactjs," indicate high usage frequency, suggesting that these languages are popular discussion topics. Smaller words represent less frequently used tags but still contribute to the overall distribution of topics.

Tags Popularity 2024 Analysis¶

This analyzes the usage trends of the 10 most frequently used tags by calculating their relative monthly changes in frequency from January to September 2024. It then creates a line chart where each line represents a tag, showing how its popularity fluctuates over time.

In [29]:
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, explode, date_format, to_date, concat, lit, lag, when
from pyspark.sql.window import Window
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Select relevant columns from the dataset (assumes df_posts contains "TagsTokens" and "CreationDate")
df_tags_analysis = df_posts.select("TagsTokens", "CreationDate")

# Explode the TagsTokens array so that each tag appears in its own row
df_tags_analysis = df_tags_analysis.withColumn("Tag", explode(col("TagsTokens")))

# Compute the total count of each tag and extract the top 10 most frequent tags
tag_totals = df_tags_analysis.groupBy("Tag").count()
top_tags = [row["Tag"] for row in tag_totals.orderBy(col("count").desc()).limit(10).collect()]

# Filter the dataset to only include rows with the top 10 tags
df_tags_analysis = df_tags_analysis.filter(col("Tag").isin(top_tags))

# Extract the year and month from CreationDate to group tag usage by month
df_tags_analysis = df_tags_analysis.withColumn("YearMonth", date_format(col("CreationDate"), "yyyy-MM"))

# Count occurrences of each tag per month
df_tags_analysis = df_tags_analysis.groupBy("Tag", "YearMonth").count()

# Convert YearMonth into an actual date format (yyyy-MM-01) for proper sorting
df_monthly_count = df_tags_analysis.withColumn(
    "MonthDate", to_date(concat(col("YearMonth"), lit("-01")), "yyyy-MM-dd")
)

# Define a window function to order each tag's count chronologically by month
windowSpec = Window.partitionBy("Tag").orderBy("MonthDate")

# Retrieve the previous month's count for each tag to compute relative changes
df_monthly_count = df_monthly_count.withColumn("prev_count", lag("count").over(windowSpec))

# Compute the relative change in tag count compared to the previous month
# The first month has no previous data, so we set its change to 0%
df_monthly_count = df_monthly_count.withColumn(
    "rel_change",
    when(col("prev_count").isNull(), 0)
    .otherwise((col("count") - col("prev_count")) / col("prev_count") * 100)
)

# Collect processed data for visualization
result = {}

for tag in top_tags:
    try:
        # Retrieve the data for each tag, ordered by month
        rows = df_monthly_count.filter(col("Tag") == tag).orderBy("MonthDate").select("YearMonth", "rel_change").collect()
        months = [int(row["YearMonth"][-2:]) for row in rows if row["YearMonth"]]  # Extract numerical month values
        changes = [row["rel_change"] for row in rows]
        result[tag] = (months, changes)
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error processing tag '{tag}': {e}")

# Plot the relative changes in tag usage over time
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

for tag, (months, changes) in result.items():
    plt.plot(months, changes, marker="o", label=tag)

plt.xlabel("Month")
plt.ylabel("Relative change of tag counts (%)")
plt.title("Relative change of the tag counts of the 10 most used tags from January to September 2024")
plt.legend()

# Adjust x-axis labels to show months
plt.xticks(range(1, 10), ["Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun", "Jul", "Aug", "Sep"])
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The graph displays relative changes in tag usage over time. Most tags show moderate fluctuations, but some (e.g., "python" in September) exhibit sharper increases or decreases, indicating trends. The dip in June suggests a period where tag usage declined across multiple languages before rebounding in July.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

                                  .sum("question_count") \

    heatmap_data = df_heatmap.orderBy("weekday_num").collect()
except Exception as e:
    print(f"Error while collecting heatmap data: {e}")

Knowledge Gap¶

What is a knowledge gap?¶

The KnowledgeGap metric is a way to measure how much a programming language struggles with unanswered questions. Instead of just counting the total number of unanswered questions, which can be misleading since languages with more total questions naturally have more unanswered ones, this method looks at two important factors:

Unanswered Ratio¶

This represents the fraction of unanswered questions relative to the total number of questions in that language. It is calculated as:

$$ UnansweredRatio = \frac{\text{TotalQuestions} - \text{AnsweredQuestions}}{\text{TotalQuestions}} $$

A higher value means a larger percentage of questions in that language are going unanswered.

Unanswered View Impact¶

This measures how often unanswered questions are viewed compared to other languages. If a question is seen by many people but still remains unanswered, it suggests a bigger knowledge gap. This is calculated as:

$$ UnansweredViewImpact = \frac{\text{AvgUnansweredViews}}{\max(\text{AvgUnansweredViews})} $$

The highest average view count among all languages is used as the reference point to scale the values between 0 and 1.

Final Knowledge Gap Calculation¶

Finally, the KnowledgeGap score is computed by multiplying these two factors:

$$ KnowledgeGap = UnansweredRatio \times UnansweredViewImpact $$

This method makes sure that languages with a high proportion of unanswered questions AND high visibility of those questions are recognized as having a greater knowledge gap. It provides a fairer comparison by not just looking at raw numbers but also considering how much people struggle to find answers despite high interest.

Aggregating Data¶

This section aggregates data per language, calculating key statistics like total questions, answered questions, and unanswered question ratios. It also computes the average number of views for unanswered questions, which indicates how often unanswered questions are still viewed.

In [34]:
# Group by post ID and select the first encountered programming language as the primary language for that post
df_knowledge_gap = df_knowledge_gap.groupBy("Id") \
    .agg(
        first("TagsTokensExploded").alias("PrimaryLanguage"),
        max("ViewCount").alias("ViewCount"),
        max("AnswerCount").alias("AnswerCount")
    )

# Drop the ID column as it's no longer needed
df_knowledge_gap = df_knowledge_gap.drop("Id")

# Aggregate metrics for each programming language
df_agg = df_knowledge_gap.groupBy("PrimaryLanguage").agg(
    count("*").alias("TotalQuestions"),  # Total number of questions per language
    count(when(col("AnswerCount") > 0, 1)).alias("AnsweredQuestions")  # Count only answered questions
)

# Calculate the ratio of unanswered questions per language
df_agg = df_agg.withColumn("UnansweredRatio", (col("TotalQuestions") - col("AnsweredQuestions")) / col("TotalQuestions"))

# Calculate the average number of views for unanswered questions per language
df_unanswered_views = df_knowledge_gap.filter(col("AnswerCount") == 0).groupBy("PrimaryLanguage").agg(
    avg("ViewCount").alias("AvgUnansweredViews")
)

# Merge unanswered view count data
df_agg = df_agg.join(df_unanswered_views, "PrimaryLanguage", "left")

Calculating the Knowledge Gap Score¶

This section calculates the "Knowledge Gap Score", which is the product of the unanswered ratio and the relative impact of unanswered views. The resulting score helps identify languages where questions often go unanswered but are still frequently viewed, indicating a gap in available expertise.

In [35]:
# Define a window function to allow scaling calculations
window_spec = Window.rowsBetween(Window.unboundedPreceding, Window.unboundedFollowing)

# Normalize unanswered views impact by dividing by the maximum value
df_agg = df_agg.withColumn(
    "UnansweredViewImpact",
    when(col("AvgUnansweredViews").isNotNull() & (max("AvgUnansweredViews").over(window_spec) > 0),
         col("AvgUnansweredViews") / max("AvgUnansweredViews").over(window_spec)
    ).otherwise(0)  # If denominator is 0, set impact to 0
)

# Compute the final Knowledge Gap Score by multiplying UnansweredRatio with UnansweredViewImpact
df_agg = df_agg.withColumn("KnowledgeGap", col("UnansweredRatio") * col("UnansweredViewImpact"))

# Sort results by Knowledge Gap Score in descending order
df_agg = df_agg.orderBy(col("KnowledgeGap").desc())

# Display the final dataset
df_agg.select("PrimaryLanguage", "TotalQuestions", "AnsweredQuestions", "UnansweredRatio", "AvgUnansweredViews", "UnansweredViewImpact", "KnowledgeGap").show(50, truncate=10)

Task 1: Primary Language Detection¶

Task Overview¶

This section focuses on predicting the primary programming language of a given text-based question. The task is formulated as a multiclass classification problem, where a machine learning model assigns each question to one of several possible programming languages based on its textual content.

Question: What programming language does a question belong to?

Dataset and Features
The dataset consists of tokenized text and tags extracted from programming-related questions. The following columns are used for training:

  • TextTokens – Tokenized representation of the question’s text
  • TagTokens – Tokenized representation of the associated tags

To handle computational constraints, only a 10% sample of the original dataset is used for training, as running model training and cross-validation on the full dataset would be too resource-intensive for the current cluster.

Machine Learning Models
Three different classification models are trained and evaluated:

  • Logistic Regression
  • Naive Bayes
  • Random Forest Classifier

For each model, the process consists of three key steps:

  1. Model Building – Constructing the model, defining the pipeline, and setting up cross-validation
  2. Training and Checkpointing – Either loading a previously trained model or training a new model and saving it
  3. Evaluation – Computing classification metrics to compare model performance

Pipeline Construction
To transform raw text into a format suitable for classification, a five-step preprocessing pipeline is implemented:

  1. Tokenization (Preprocessed before pipeline)
  2. Count Vectorization – Converts text into raw term frequency vectors
  3. IDF Transformation – Adjusts term frequencies based on their importance across documents
  4. String Indexing – Converts categorical language labels into numerical indices
  5. Model Addition – Attaches the classification model at the final stage

Cross-Validation and Hyperparameter Tuning
To improve model performance, cross-validation is applied with a predefined hyperparameter grid. The tuning process focuses on maximizing accuracy, adjusting parameters such as:

  • Vocabulary size for CountVectorizer
  • Regularization parameter for Logistic Regression
  • Smoothing parameter for Naive Bayes
  • Tree count and depth for Random Forest

Model Selection
At the end of the process, the best-performing model is selected based on evaluation metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall and F1-score. The results provide insights into how well each model differentiates between programming languages based on textual patterns.

Model Building¶

Predefined Steps¶

Define Pipeline Modules¶

Here 3 moduls used for the machine learning Pipelines are defined:

  1. CountVectorizer: This module converts the tokenized text into a vector of raw term frequencies, representing how often each word appears in a document. It builds a vocabulary of up to 5000 words, ignoring words that appear in fewer than 5 documents to filter out rare terms.

  2. IDF (Inverse Document Frequency): This transformation adjusts the raw term frequencies by reducing the weight of common words and increasing the importance of informative words. It helps highlight distinguishing words in the dataset by computing their relevance across multiple documents.

  3. StringIndexer: This module converts the PrimaryLanguage categorical labels into numerical indices, which are required for machine learning models. Each language is assigned a unique integer, enabling the classifier to process text labels as numerical values.

In [42]:
# Transform the tokenized text (TextTokens) into a vector of raw term frequencies
countVectorizer = CountVectorizer(inputCol="TextTokens", outputCol="raw_features", vocabSize=5000, minDF=5)

# Apply the IDF (Inverse Document Frequency) transformation to the raw term frequency vector
idf = IDF(inputCol="raw_features", outputCol="features")

# Convert the PrimaryLanguage from string labels to numerical indices (required for machine learning algorithm)
label_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol="PrimaryLanguage", outputCol="label")

Define Classification Evaluators¶

Here multiple evaluators for assessing the performance of a classification model are defined. There are 4 different metrics:

  • Accuracy: Computes the overall classification accuracy by comparing predicted and actual labels.

  • Precision: Calculates the weighted precision, which measures how many predicted positive instances are actually correct, accounting for class imbalances.

  • Recall: Determines the weighted recall, which evaluates how well the model identifies actual instances of each class.

  • F1 Score Evaluator: Computes the F1 score, which balances precision and recall to provide a single performance metric.

In [43]:

Logistic Regression¶

How does a Logistic Regression work?

Logistic Regression is a classification algorithm that predicts the probability of an instance belonging to a certain class. It works by applying the logistic (sigmoid) function to a weighted sum of input features, producing a probability score between 0 and 1.

For multiclass classification, Logistic Regression uses the softmax function instead of the sigmoid, assigning a probability to each possible class. The model is trained by adjusting weights to minimize the difference between predicted probabilities and actual labels using optimization techniques like gradient descent.

Pipeline and Model Building¶

In [44]:

Naive Bayes¶

How does the Naive Bayes work?

Naive Bayes is a probabilistic classification algorithm based on Bayes' theorem, which calculates the probability of a class given the input features. It assumes that all features are independent (hence "naive") and contribute equally to the classification, making it computationally efficient.

For multiclass classification, Naive Bayes estimates the probability of each class using the frequency of words in the training data. The model applies the multinomial distribution, which is commonly used for text classification tasks like spam filtering and language detection. The smoothing parameter (smoothing=1.0) prevents zero probabilities by assigning small values to unseen words, improving generalization.

Pipeline and Model Building¶

Random Forest Classifier¶

How does a Random Forest Classifier work?

Random Forest is an ensemble learning method that combines multiple decision trees to improve classification performance. Each tree in the forest is trained on a random subset of the data (using bootstrapping) and makes an independent prediction. The final classification is determined by majority voting, where the most frequently predicted class is selected.

For multiclass classification, Random Forest builds multiple decision trees that split the data based on the most informative features at each step. This method reduces overfitting compared to a single decision tree and increases generalization. Random Forest also supports feature importance scoring, helping to identify the most influential variables in the dataset.

Pipeline and Model Building¶

In [50]:

# Create a parameter grid:
# Random Forest tuning: number of trees and max depth
q1_paramGrid_rf = (ParamGridBuilder()
                   .addGrid(q1_rf.numTrees, [10, 20, 30])
                   .addGrid(q1_rf.maxDepth, [5, 10, 15])
                   .build())

# Create the CrossValidator for RandomForest
# Evaluator = accuracy (metric the CV try to maximize)

                                estimatorParamMaps=q1_paramGrid_rf,
                                evaluator=accuracy_evaluator,
                                numFolds=2)

Top 10 predictors (words) for each language¶

This extracts the Naive Bayes model, retrieves the vocabulary and original language labels, then identifies the top 10 most influential words for each programming language based on the learned log-probabilities and presents them in a Spark DataFrame.

In [57]:
import numpy as np
from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType, FloatType

# The pipeline stages for the LogisticRegression were:
#  0: CountVectorizerModel
#  1: IDFModel
#  2: StringIndexerModel (for labels)
#  3: LogisticRegressionModel

# Get the vocabulary from the CountVectorizer
q1_bestmodel_cv = q1_bestmodel.stages[0]
q1_bestmodel_vocab = q1_bestmodel_cv.vocabulary

# Get the label mapping from the StringIndexer
label_indexer = q1_bestmodel.stages[2]
languages = label_indexer.labels

# Get the coefficient matrix from the LogisticRegression
lr_model = q1_bestmodel.stages[3]
coef_matrix = lr_model.coefficientMatrix.toArray()

# Find top 10 words ranked by coefficient value for each languageFor each language
top_words_by_language = {}
for idx, language in enumerate(languages):
    # Get indices of the top 10 coefficients in descending order
    top10_indices = np.argsort(coef_matrix[idx])[::-1][:10]
    # Map indices to words
    top_words_by_language[language] = [q1_bestmodel_vocab[i] for i in top10_indices]

# Each row is a dictionary with key "rank" and one key for each language.
data = []
for rank in range(10):
    row = [rank + 1]  # first column: rank
    for language in languages:
        row.append(top_words_by_language[language][rank])
    data.append(row)

# Create a spark df from the results
columns = ["rank"] + languages
top_predictors_df = spark.createDataFrame(data, columns)

top_predictors_df.show(truncate=20)

Task 2: Engagement Clustering¶

Task Overview¶

This section focuses on clustering the question based on 3 choosen metrics.

Question: What internal groups consists in the StackOverflow questions?

Dataset and Features
The following columns are used for training:

  • LogViewsPerDay – Tokenized representation of the question’s text
  • EngagementRatio – Tokenized representation of the associated tags

To handle computational constraints, only a 10% sample of the original dataset is used for training, as running model training and cross-validation on the full dataset would be too resource-intensive for the current cluster.

Machine Learning Models
A k-means clustering model is used for clustering the questions.

The process consists of three key steps:

  1. Finding k - Finding k (number of clusters)
  2. Model Building – Constructing the model, defining the pipeline, and setting up cross-validation
  3. Training and Checkpointing – Either loading a previously trained model or training a new model and saving it
  4. Evaluation – Plotting the clusters and checking the avg metrics per cluster

Pipeline Construction
To transform raw text into a format suitable for classification, a five-step preprocessing pipeline is implemented:

  1. Vector Assembly
  2. Standard Scaling

Finding optimal k
To find the optimal number of clusters the following techniques are used:

  1. Silhoutte Score
  2. Elbow Method

Because there are negative values in the LogScore which should be handled somehow. A good way to do this is just to shift them. This means we take the minimum score and shift all the values by as much so that the minimum score is above 0.

Model Building¶

Pipeline Modules¶

Here 2 stages used for the machine learning Pipelines are defined:

  • VectorAssembler: This module combines multiple numerical features (e.g., log-transformed views, engagement ratio, and log score) into a single feature vector.

  • StandardScaler: The StandardScaler normalizes the assembled feature vectors by removing the mean and scaling to unit variance. This ensures that all features contribute equally to the clustering algorithm, preventing dominance by features with larger scales.

In [66]:
# Assemble Feature Vectors

q2_df = q2_scaler.fit(q2_df).transform(q2_df)

Finding best k¶

Silhouette Score¶

The silhouette score measures how well-separated and cohesive clusters are in a clustering model. It ranges from -1 to 1, where:

  • 1 → Clusters are well-separated, and points are close to their own cluster.
  • 0 → Clusters overlap, meaning points are on the boundary between clusters.
  • -1 → Points are assigned to the wrong cluster.

A higher silhouette score means that the clustering is more meaningful, with well-defined groups.

In [67]:
q2_cost = []
q2_silhouette_scores = {}

# Specify range of k, which will be tested
q2_k_values = range(2, 10)

for k in q2_k_values:
    q2_kmeans = KMeans(k=k, seed=1234, featuresCol="features")
    q2_model = q2_kmeans.fit(q2_df)
    
    q2_clustered = q2_model.transform(q2_df)
    
    q2_cost.append(q2_model.summary.trainingCost)
    
    q2_evaluator = ClusteringEvaluator(featuresCol="features", metricName="silhouette")
    q2_score = q2_evaluator.evaluate(q2_clustered)  # use q2_evaluator and q2_clustered here
    q2_silhouette_scores[k] = q2_score
    print(f"k={k}, Silhouette Score={q2_score:.4f}")

Elbow Method¶

The elbow method is another technique used to determine the optimal number of clusters (k). It works by plotting the training cost (inertia) against different values of k.

  • As k increases, the training cost decreases because clusters get smaller.
  • The "elbow point" is where the rate of decrease slows down significantly, forming a bend in the curve.
  • This point represents the best balance between minimizing cost and avoiding too many clusters, ensuring meaningful grouping without overfitting.
In [69]:
k_values = list(q2_k_values)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
plt.plot(k_values, q2_cost)
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters (k)")
plt.ylabel("Training Cost")
plt.title("Elbow Method: Training Cost vs. k")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Best k¶

The optimal number of clusters in this case is k=4 because it has the highest silhouette score (0.5438), indicating that clusters are well-separated and compact, leading to a more meaningful grouping. Additionally, the elbow method suggests that k=4 is a turning point where adding more clusters results in diminishing improvements in training cost, making it a balanced choice between interpretability and performance.

        # Load pre-trained model

Interpretation and Results¶

Cluster 0: Low-Engagement, Low-Quality Questions

  • Avg_ViewsPerDay: 0.47 (Very low visibility)
  • Avg_EngagementRatio: 0.0216 (Low interaction)
  • Avg_Score: 0.10 (Poorly rated)
  • Avg_Answers: 0.57 (Few answers)
  • Avg_Comments: 0.87 (Minimal discussion)
  • Interpretation: These questions receive little attention, few answers, and low ratings. They might be unclear, unhelpful, or niche topics with low interest.

Cluster 1: High-View, Low-Quality Questions

  • Avg_ViewsPerDay: 4.24 (High visibility)
  • Avg_EngagementRatio: 0.0175 (Extremely low interaction)
  • Avg_Score: 0.22 (Low-rated)
  • Avg_Answers: 0.95 (Moderate answer rate)
  • Avg_Comments: 1.65 (Some discussion)
  • Interpretation: These questions attract many views but low engagement, suggesting they may be clickbaity, unclear, or too broad.

Cluster 2: Niche, Highly Discussed Questions

  • Avg_ViewsPerDay: 0.55 (Moderate visibility)
  • Avg_EngagementRatio: 0.1188 (High interaction)
  • Avg_Score: 0.03 (Very low ratings)
  • Avg_Answers: 0.75 (Few answers)
  • Avg_Comments: 5.08 (Extensive discussion)
  • Interpretation: These questions don’t get many views but generate significant discussion, likely because they are opinion-based, complex, or difficult to answer.

Cluster 3: High-Quality, Well-Engaged Questions

  • Avg_ViewsPerDay: 2.71 (Moderately high visibility)
  • Avg_EngagementRatio: 0.0278 (Decent interaction)
  • Avg_Score: 2.78 (Highly rated)
  • Avg_Answers: 1.23 (Most likely to be answered)
  • Avg_Comments: 2.09 (Active discussion)
  • Interpretation: These are high-quality questions with good engagement, attracting both answers and discussion. They are likely well-structured, clear, and valuable to the community.

Strengths & Shortcomings

Overall the clustering clearly differentiates between low- vs. high-quality and low- vs. high-engagement questions. Nevertheless, there is room for improvment, which could potentially be the following:

  1. Refine variables used for clustering, which means using maybe other variables or additional one's might result in better clustering.
  2. Use other clustering algorithms like (DBSCAN or hierachical clustering).
  3. Change the feature engineering (like log or standard scaling) to other techniques.
